<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910226-0066</DOCNO><DOCID>910226-0066.</DOCID><HL>   Grumman Overhauls   Operating Structure,   Forms 4 New Groups</HL><DATE>02/26/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A6</SO><CO>   GQ WNEWS</CO><IN>AEROSPACE (ARO)</IN><LP>   BETHPAGE, N.Y. -- Grumman Corp. said four new operatinggroups will supplant its seven existing divisions in astructural change aimed at cutting back on the number ofexecutives directly reporting to its top brass. A spokeswomanfor the company said no layoffs would occur as a result ofthe changes.   The four new groups are the Aircraft group, the Systemsgroup, the Data Systems andamp; Services group, and the Alliedgroup. As part of the changes, the company's Space StationProgram Support division and Melbourne Systems division werefolded into its Systems group. The Technical Servicesdivision was folded into the Data Systems andamp; Services group.</LP><TEXT>   In addition, the company said Albert Verderosa, 58 yearsold, previously the Melbourne Systems division president,succeeds recently retired Thomas Guarino as president of theSystems group. Jacob J. Bussolini, 55, formerly vicepresident, business operations, was named to the new positionof vice president, strategic planning. Steven Dely, 47, waselected to the new position of vice president, executivestaff, while retaining his position as staff vice presidentand assistant to the chairman. Robert W. Bradshaw, 61, vicepresident, human resources and administration and corporatesecretary, has added responsibility for the facilitiesengineering and operations departments.</TEXT></DOC>